{{also|larĝe|Large}}
==English==
{{wikipedia|large (disambiguation)|large}}
===Etymology===
From {{der|en|enm|large}}, from {{der|en|fro|large}}, from {{der|en|la|larga}}, feminine of {{m|la|largus||abundant, plentiful, copious, large, much}}, of uncertain ultimate origin; see there for more. Mostly displaced {{cog|enm|stoor|stoor, stour|large, great}} (from {{cog|ang|stōr}}) and {{m|enm|muchel||large, great}} (from {{cog|ang|myċel}}).
===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|en|/lɑːd͡ʒ/}}
* {{a|GA}} {{IPA|en|/lɑɹd͡ʒ/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-large.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{audio|en|En-uk-large.ogg|Audio (UK)}}
* {{rhymes|en|ɑː(ɹ)dʒ|s=1}}
===Adjective===
{{en-adj|er}}
# Of [[considerable]] or [[relatively]] [[great]] [[size]] or [[extent]].
#* {{RQ:Churchill Celebrity|chapter=2|passage=We drove back to the office with some concern on my part at the prospect of so '''large''' a case. Sunning himself on the board steps, I saw for the first time Mr. Farquhar Fenelon Cooke.}}
#: {{ux|en|Russia is a '''large''' country.&emsp;The fruit-fly has '''large''' eyes for its body size.&emsp;He has a '''large''' collection of stamps.}}
# {{lb|en|especially|clothing|food|or|drink}} That is large {{gl|the manufactured size}}.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} Abundant; ample.
#* {{RQ:Milton Paradise Lost|book=5|passage=We have yet '''large''' day.}}
# {{lb|en|archaic}} Full in statement; diffuse; profuse.
#* {{RQ:Felton Classics}}
#*: I might be very '''large''' upon the importance and advantages of education.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} Free; unencumbered.
#* {{RQ:Fairfax Godfrey of Bulloigne}}
#*: Of burdens all he set the Paynims '''large'''.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} Unrestrained by decorum; said of language.
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Much Ado About Nothing|act=II|scene=iii|passage=Some '''large''' jests he will make.}}
# {{lb|en|nautical}} Crossing the line of a ship's course in a favorable direction; said of the wind when it is [[abeam]], or between the beam and the quarter.
